com.bluegosling.apt.reflect

Class ArTypeVariable<D extends ArGenericDeclaration>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.bluegosling.apt.reflect.ArTypeVariable<D>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ArType

    public class ArTypeVariable<D extends ArGenericDeclaration>
extends Object
implements ArType
    A type variable. Type variables are declared on generic classes and interfaces and then used in type specifications in the class. For example, the class ArrayList has a type parameter (E) and a method that is declared as boolean add(E). In the method signature, the generic type of the one parameter is a reference to the type variable. This is analogous to TypeVariable, except that it represents types in Java source (during annotation processing) vs. representing runtime types.
    See Also:
    TypeVariable

      • getBounds

        public List<? extends ArType> getBounds()
        Returns the upper bounds (aka "extends" bounds) for this type variable. For example in the declaration Interface<T extends SomeClass & Cloneable & Serializable>, the type variable T has three bounds: SomeClass, Cloneable, and Serializable. If a type variable has no bounds defined then the implicit upper bound is java.lang.Object.
        Returns:
        the upper bounds for this type variable

      • getGenericDeclaration

        public D getGenericDeclaration()
        Returns the declaration for this type variable. This will be either a Class, ArMethod, or ArConstructor, depending on where the type variable was declared.

        If the type variable is a captured wildcard then this method returns null.

        Returns:
        the generic declaration that declared this type variable

        public String toTypeString()
        Description copied from interface: ArType
        Returns a string representation of this type, suitable for constructing a representation of this type that could be used in Java source code. For most types, this is the same as toString(), but one glaring exception to that is in ArClass where toString() and toGenericString() return representations that resemble type declarations but toTypeString() returns a string that is a simple reference to the class's raw/erased type.
